04734nam a22008055i 9781501729966DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017299667 a10.7591/97815017299662doi  a(DE-B1597)515116  a(OCoLC)1083628683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHG2040.5.U5bS747 2003eb 7aPOL0290002bisacsh04a332.7/22/09732221 aStuart, Guy, eauthor.10aDiscriminating Risk :bThe U.S. Mortgage Lending Industry in the Twentieth Century /cGuy Stuart. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource :b6 charts/graphs, 4 maps, 2 halftones, 1 line drawing, 11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Meaning of Value -- t2. Rules for Assessing the Borrower and Managing Behavioral Risk -- t3. The Loan Application Process -- t4. Constructing Housing Markets -- t5. Lending Discrimination -- t6. Constructing Risk -- t7. New Policy Approaches to Discrimination and Subprime Lending -- tAppendix -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe U.S. home mortgage industry first formalized risk criteria in the 1920s and 1930s to determine which applicants should receive funds. Over the past eighty years, these formulae have become more sophisticated. Guy Stuart demonstrates that the very concepts on which lenders base their decisions reflect a set of social and political values about "who deserves what." Stuart examines the fine line between licit choice and illicit discrimination, arguing that lenders, while eradicating blatantly discriminatory practices, have ignored the racial and economic-class biases that remain encoded in their decision processes. He explains why African Americans and Latinos continue to be at a disadvantage in gaining access to loans: discrimination, he finds, results from the interaction between the way lenders make decisions and the way they shape the social structure of the mortgage and housing markets.Mortgage lenders, Stuart contends, are embedded in and shape a social context that can best be understood in terms of rules, networks, and the production of space. Stuart's history of lenders' risk criteria reveals that they were synthesized from rules of thumb, cultural norms, and untested theories. In addition, his interviews with real estate and lending professionals in the Chicago housing market show us how the criteria are implemented today. Drawing on census and Home Mortgage Disclosure Act data for quantitative support, Stuart concludes with concrete policy proposals that take into account the social structure in which lenders make decisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aDiscrimination in housingzIllinoiszChicago. 0aDiscrimination in housingzUnited States. 0aMortgage loanszUnited States. 0aRace discriminationzUnited States. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501729966423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501729966.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG